Ksenia Lutskina is a Belarusian journalist who worked for the state broadcaster before resigning in protest during the 2020 anti-government demonstrations. Alongside many colleagues, she supported independent reporting on mass protests after the disputed presidential election. When the government cracked down on dissent, Ksenia joined a media initiative that aimed to provide accurate coverage. In December 2020, she was arrested as part of a sweeping repression against independent voices and accused of attempting to "undermine national security."

She was later sentenced to 8 years in prison, allegedly for her journalistic activities and connections to opposition groups. Her health deteriorated significantly in custody, and international organizations raised concerns about the denial of medical care. Her case highlights how simple reporting and organizing information in a restricted environment can be perceived as a threat.

In environments like hers, tools that don’t rely on the internet or SIM networks help reduce risk. Journalists often need to exchange sensitive material securely and discreetly—especially when normal channels are monitored. Her story connects to broader terms like offline encryption, air-gapped tools, metadata resistance, and independent media under repression.